State National Companies: Completely Ignored And Severely Mispriced - State National Companies, Inc. (NASDAQ:SNC) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»State National Companies: Completely Ignored And Severely MispricedApr.15.15 | About: State National (SNC) Sebastian Grimberg Special situations, value




SummaryState National Companies is a specialty provider of P&C insurance operating in two niche markets across the U.S.Unlike most P&C insurers, State National's unique business model and sustainable competitive advantages translate into consistent and relatively high returns on equity, with low financial leverage.One-timers are hiding the company's earning power, allowing prospective investors to acquire the company at a truly cheap price.During the course of this year, the stock should start "screening well," and institutional investors will discover the name.Management has the financial flexibility to buy back stock without altering the company's investments in future growth.State National Companies (NASDAQ:SNC) is neither a broken story nor a turnaround. Quite the contrary, it is a profitable, growing enterprise whose share price is temporally disconnected from its business reality. The company's improving fundamentals are grounded in its solid foundation. The Ledbetter family and the company's employees have done an outstanding job in building a great business in a highly competitive industry. They discovered a market niche, opportunistically expanded it and repeated the process. If management preserves this disciplined approach going forward, State National offers a significant asymmetric risk-reward profile at the current market price, with probability of permanent capital loss close to 0 and at least a 50% return from current prices. P&C Insurance 101 Insurance companies primarily make money by charging premiums to policyholders for insurance coverage of risks facing the policyholder. Since the idea to be paid for holding other people's money is quite enticing, the industry attracts intense competition. Furthermore, most insureds don't care from whom they buy, making insurance a commodity-like product. P&C insurance companies specialize in specific lines of businesses (auto, homeowners' and workers' compensation are a few of the more commonly known lines of business), but in most cases, that's not enough to overcome unfavorable industry dynamics. As a result, a typical insurance company underwrites at a loss, makes profits investing its float (money the company does not own, but temporally holds), and generates economic value if its "cost of float" is less than the cost the company would otherwise incur to obtain funds. As we'll see below, State National is an atypical insurance company in the sense that the company creates economic value in a different way.
 What does SNC do? Founded in 1973 by brothers Lonnie Ledbetter and Terry Ledbetter, State National Companies is a specialty provider of P&C insurance operating in two niche markets across the U.S.: Program Services and Collateral Protection Insurance (CPI). In the Program Services segment, SNC leverages its A.M. Best "A" (Excellent) rating, licenses and reputation to provide access to the U.S. property and casualty insurance market: the company offers issuing carrier capacity to general agents or producers in exchange for a ceding fee, and reinsures all the underwriting and operating risk associated with these arrangements. In the Lender Services segment, SNC specializes in providing collateral protection insurance, which insures personal automobiles and other vehicles held as collateral for loans made by credit unions, banks and specialty finance lenders. In other words, when a borrower does not uphold its obligation to insure the collateral underlying the loan, the lender can pay the company for CPI and then add the cost of CPI to the borrower's loan. A more detailed review of each business is presented below. Program Services Business The Program Services Business is the biggest contributor to earnings (72% of 2014 adjusted pre-tax income) and what mainly sets apart the company from a typical insurer. The company provides issuing carrier capacity in exchange for a fee (around 5% of gross written premium), and reinsures substantially all of the underwriting and business risk. As you can see in the following picture, in this segment, SNC looks like an insurance broker:  Business is originated from general agents (GA) or capacity providers (CP). In the case of GAs, they seek to provide customized insurance solutions that require an A.M. Best "A"-rated carrier (SNC retains an A.M Best "A" rating since 1993). In the case of CPs, some of the reasons include: insurers that have access to origination but require an A.M Best "A" rating or broader licensing (SNC's subsidiaries are admitted carriers licensed to write property and casualty business in all 50 states and the District of Columbia); foreign insurers writing in the U.S.; domestic insurers seeking additional business free of channel conflicts; insurers looking to reduce financial leverage; institutional risk investors (including hedge funds and other investment funds), among others. Contracts are designed in a manner that:
 A) GAs and CPs are obliged to deal with each other, with GAs providing policy administration, claims handling, cash handling, underwriting, or other traditional insurance company services, and CPs monitoring the GAs. The funds for premiums, commissions, losses, assessments and other payments are settled directly between each party (SNC does not record any receivables or payables). B) All the underwriting and business risk is borne by the reinsurer. If a GA defaults on its obligation to pay ceding fees to SNC, the CP is obliged to make the payment. Therefore, the only risk retained by SNC is the credit risk of the CP, which the company mitigates by establishing strict financial criteria to select CPs, or by requiring CPs to post substantial collateral (the company holds $2 billion of collateral against $1.7B of gross recoverables as of December 31, 2014). As a result of A) and B), this segment has strong operating leverage and very few risks. SNC has ceded over $10 billion in premiums over the past 26 years, with no unpaid reinsurance recoverables. Additionally, the low-cost business model allows SNC to charge fees that are in the lower end of the market range, which is an additional attraction for GAs and CPs to work with the company. To put it simply, the business is a cash flow machine:  Some companies, including AmTrust Financial Services (NASDAQ:AFSI) and Argo Group (NASDAQ:AGII), offer issuing carrier capacity but on a limited basis, and unlike SNC, assume a portion of the underwriting risk. Lender Services Business In the Lender Services segment, the company primarily offers Collateral Protection Insurance. As is stated in the company's prospectus, "the key difference between CPI and traditional automobile physical damage coverage is that CPI is purchased by lenders to protect their interest in collateral when it has been established that a borrower has not fulfilled his or her obligation to the lending institution to purchase adequate insurance coverage". If a borrower then purchases adequate insurance coverage, the lender cancels CPI coverage. The following diagram explains the business:
  So far, State National has been focused on the credit union space, where the company spots a leading market share of approx. 25%. This was mainly achieved through an agreement with CUNA Mutual. CUNA Mutual is an insurer that has relationships with 95% of the nation's credit unions. The joint venture allows SNC to leverage on these relationships and CUNA Mutual's substantial sales force (approx. 200 people). In turn, CUNA Mutual outsources CPI administration, claims handling and other aspects of the business to SNC, which is the only pure-play, vertical integrated CPI provider. A key component of this segment's value proposition is "InsurTrak", a proprietary insurance tracking system. The platform delivers real-time visibility into the current borrower insurance information, and management believes it is highly scalable, with little incremental cost (don't bother to find this asset on the company's balance sheet). The company's expertise in the space, its strategic alliance with CUNA Mutual and the strong value proposition in the form of "InsurTrak" translate into an average combined ratio of 88% during the last three years. What is also encouraging about this segment is its growth potential. For the year end 2014, 6% of earned premium derived from banks and specialty lenders, and management believes this market is bigger than the credit union space. If, for the sake of simplicity, we assume that the market size is the same, and that the company will be able to achieve a 25% market share through a CUNA Mutual type joint venture, this segment has the potential to double from current levels, with little incremental costs. SNC has hired additional dedicated sales staff to address this market.
 Adding the two together When you add the two operating segments together, the result is a company with the following attributes: 
Profitability across market cycles. The company has a 25-year track record of profitability.
Since the company retains no underwriting risk in the Program Services business and CPI is a low-limit, short-tail business (time between the event and the settlement), the overall business is quite predictable, which allows SNC to operate at a relatively high premium/surplus leverage:
  Mid-teens adj. ROE, with low financial leverage. It is worth noting that in 2014, the company achieved a 15% ROE, with a 65% increase in equity relative to 2013 due to the private placement. In its last 10-K, it is stated that the company's objective is to "maintain a financial leverage ratio in the range of 20% to 40%" (page 66). As you can see in the following table, if we take the middle range of that guidance, which is in line with 2013's equity, the company would have achieved a 20% ROE in 2014: 
 Valuation If we think that for the above reasons, SNC will continue to operate profitably in the future, the company's net cash and investments should be value-added. Prospective investors would also be willing to pay a multiple for the company's adj. net income, which, in this case, is a proxy for free cash flow. 
 Note: 
SNC's market cap is based on 44.2 million shares outstanding as of April 10, 2015 and a $10.0 share price.
2015 Adj. net income is estimated based on management's projections for ceding fees, earned premiums and combined ratios for year-end 2015, taking the most conservative projections in each case.
 A 10 multiple for an overcapitalized, mid-teens ROE, insurance broker-type business that has been profitable during the past 26 years seems low. It also worth noting that adj. net income has grown at a 20% CAGR during the past three years. But even if the multiple doesn't expand and the business doesn't grow much going forward, prospective investors still get a 50% return at current market prices. Moreover, in case the mispricing persists, management has the financial flexibility to create shareholder value by selling a small portion of the company's investment portfolio (currently yielding 2.8%) and buying back common stock. Why the opportunity exists 
Market participants are completely ignoring this company. In its first conference call as a public company, there were no questions, and in the second call, only Bob Ramsey from FBR Capital asked some questions, who is the only analyst covering the company (at least publicly).
A probable reason why this company is being ignored is because one-timers are hiding the company's earnings power:
  In the above table, net income is adjusted as if SNC had been a C Corporation, publicly traded company since 2012. 2014 net income was particularly impacted by special items, with the line "Contract modification expense" deserving a special mention. Initially, SNC had a reinsurance agreement with CUNA Mutual, where the company ceded 50% of the alliance business to CUNA Mutual; additionally, CUNA Mutual reimbursed 50% of direct commissions paid to the accounts, subject to the alliance agreement. In 2014, SNC paid $17.8m to CUNA Mutual to increase its retention of the business from 50% to 70% and reduce reimbursement from 50% to 30% (those $17.8m are the $11.2m you see in the above table net of tax benefits). In short, this was an investment that the company managed to expense. These are the kind of things that distinguish managers with an owner mentality from managers that strive to maximize short-term EPS.
 By the end of this year, when the gap between real and accounting earnings will have probably narrowed, whoever runs a P/B < 2, ROE > 15% screen should find the company at the current share price. Possible share overhang from potential update of Meadowbrook's A.M Best Rating. The merger between Meadowbrook Insurance Group (NYSE:MIG) and Fosun International Limited (OTCPK:FOSUF) is expected to close in the second half of 2015. Meadowbrook accounted for 9.3% of total revenues in 2014. If the company merges with Fosun and subsequently receives a better rating from A.M Best, revenues from this customer could be impaired. Still, this is normal business for SNC (while some CPs are upgraded, others are downgraded), and the potential outcome is contemplated in management's guidance. Risks We should distinguish between business risks and risks specific to minority shareholders. Overall, the business will be fine. SNC has never lost its A.M Best "A" rating since it was first granted in 1993, and probably has never been as capitalized as it is today; its revenues are geographically diversified, which mitigates a negative regulatory outcome in a given state; the company has a good and mutually beneficial relationship with CUNA Mutual, which was recently amended. In short, prospective investors will have a hard time trying to kill this company. Maybe the biggest risk facing minority shareholders is that the company is a family business. It was founded by two brothers; the Ledbetter family owns 48.7% of total shares outstanding (as of April 10, 2015), and 3 out of 6 senior managers are from the same family. As an outsider with no connections to the family or the company's insiders, and considering its very short history as a public company, it is hard to assure that management will treat all shareholders equally. Still, common sense tells us that to build a successful enterprise, you have to be honest with all your stakeholders. In the rare occasion that this case turns out being an exception, it is worth mentioning that Fortress Investment Group (NYSE:FIG) owns 8% of total shares outstanding, and has a representative on the board. It is my impression that you don't get to actively manage $67.5B by looking aside when someone is milking you, and we would be truly unlucky if common sense fails us twice.
 Remarks SNC has a fortress balance sheet, strong free cash flow generation, sustainable competitive advantages, 26 years of profitability and an equally promising future. Once investors start discovering this gem and understand its unique business model, the opportunity to buy the company's shares at bargain prices will be probably gone.
Disclosure: The author is long SNC. 
