Foreign Domiciled Reinsurer



Fronting
New markets. Unique opportunities. Additional capacity. Increased profits. Control your destiny with State National’s fronting model. We let you create and manage your insurance program in alignment with your business strategy. As the nationally recognized leader in fronting, we provide the paper — so you can do what you do best.
Unparalleled autonomy.
We encourage you to design, control and own your program to maximize your competitive edge.
Nationwide authority.
State National’s Program Services division grants you full access and authority to ‘A’ rated paper in all 50 states through our three 
                           admitted carriers, State National Insurance Company, National Specialty Insurance Company and City National Insurance Company as well as our two excess and 
                           surplus lines carriers, United Specialty Insurance Company and Independent Specialty Insurance Company.  A.M. Best has assigned the State National Group 
                           a Financial Size Category (FSC) of IX.


“With State National, I never have to worry about my carrier’s long-term commitment to the program market. It’s what they have been doing for almost 40 years.”

Nationwide Program Manager

Keep it simple.
We don’t require time and data intensive uploads because we know your time is better spent satisfying customers.
Superior service.
A lot of companies talk about service, we live it. Our experienced staff is given the authority to enable our clients, which means you don’t get stuck in endless bureaucracy.
Authenticity.
We know who we are and, equally important, we know who we aren’t. We don’t want to be everything to everybody. We want to be integral to our customers’ success.
Efficient and effective.
By allowing program managers, reinsurers and insurance carrier partners to collaborate directly, we offer the most freedom and resources at a reasonable cost.





Fronting: The Basics
Fronting is a contractual arrangement in which an insurance carrier allows policies to be issued in its name, with all or most of the risk reinsured by a third party.
